<!-- Q1 -->
<question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>Wald - Var(S_{N+1}), N~Pois(λ), Xi~N(1,1)</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>Let \(N\sim\mathrm{Poisson}(\lambda)\) and \(X_1,X_2,\ldots\) be i.i.d. \(N(1,1)\), independent of \(N\). Define \(S=X_1+\cdots+X_{N+1}\). Then \(\mathrm{Var}(S)\) is:</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (A) \(2\lambda+1\)</strong></p><p>Let \(M=N+1\). Then \(E[M]=\lambda+1\), \(\mathrm{Var}(M)=\lambda\). By Wald's variance identity: \(\mathrm{Var}(S_M)=E[M]\cdot\mathrm{Var}(X)+\mathrm{Var}(M)\cdot(E[X])^2=(\lambda+1)(1)+\lambda(1)=2\lambda+1\).</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text>\(2\lambda+1\)</text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text>\(\lambda+1\)</text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text>\(2\lambda\)</text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text>\(\lambda+2\)</text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>

<!-- Q2 -->
<question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>Wald - E[S_N], N~Pois(2), Xi~Exp(3)</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>Let \(N\sim\mathrm{Poisson}(2)\) and \(X_i\overset{iid}{\sim}\mathrm{Exp}(3)\) (mean \(1/3\)), independent of \(N\). With \(S=X_1+\cdots+X_N\) (\(S=0\) if \(N=0\)), the value of \(E[S]\) is:</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (B) \(2/3\)</strong></p><p>Wald's first identity: \(E[S_N]=E[N]\cdot E[X_1]=2\cdot\tfrac{1}{3}=\tfrac{2}{3}\).</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
