</question>

<!-- Q4 -->
<question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>Wald - Compound Poisson Variance Formula</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>Let \(N\sim\mathrm{Poisson}(\lambda)\) and \(X_i\) i.i.d. with \(E[X_i]=\mu\), \(E[X_i^2]=\nu\), independent of \(N\). Then \(\mathrm{Var}(X_1+\cdots+X_N)\) equals:</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (C) \(\lambda\nu\)</strong></p><p>By Wald's variance formula: \(\mathrm{Var}(S)=E[N]\mathrm{Var}(X)+\mathrm{Var}(N)(E[X])^2=\lambda(\nu-\mu^2)+\lambda\mu^2=\lambda\nu\). This is the standard compound Poisson variance formula.</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text>\(\lambda\mu\)</text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text>\(\lambda(\nu-\mu^2)\)</text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text>\(\lambda\nu\)</text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text>\(\lambda^2\nu\)</text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>

<!-- Q5 -->
<question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>Wald - First Identity Statement</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>Let \(X_1,X_2,\ldots\) be i.i.d. with mean \(\mu\), and \(N\) a stopping time with \(E[N]<\infty\), independent in the Wald sense. Then \(E\!\left[\sum_{i=1}^N X_i\right]\) equals:</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (A) \(\mu\cdot E[N]\)</strong></p><p>Wald's first identity: \(E[S_N]=\mu\cdot E[N]\). This holds whenever \(N\) is a stopping time with \(E[N]<\infty\). It generalises the linearity of expectation to random sample sizes.</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
  <defaultgrade>1.0</defaultgrade><penalty>0.25</penalty><hidden>0</hidden>
  <single>true</single><shuffleanswers>true</shuffleanswers><answernumbering>abc</answernumbering>
  <answer fraction="100" format="html"><text>\(\mu\cdot E[N]\)</text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text>\(\mu^2\cdot E[N]\)</text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text>\(\mu\cdot E[N^2]\)</text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
  <answer fraction="0" format="html"><text>\(\mu/E[N]\)</text><feedback format="html"><text></text></feedback></answer>
</question>

<!-- Q6 -->
<question type="multichoice">
  <name><text>Wald - Pois(3) Bernoulli(1/2) Compound Sum Variance</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p>Let \(N\sim\mathrm{Poisson}(3)\) and \(X_i\overset{iid}{\sim}\mathrm{Bernoulli}(1/2)\), independent of \(N\). Then \(\mathrm{Var}(X_1+\cdots+X_N)\) is:</p>]]></text></questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html"><text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Answer: (B) \(3/2\)</strong></p><p>Since \(X\sim\mathrm{Bernoulli}(1/2)\), \(E[X^2]=E[X]=1/2\). By compound Poisson: \(\mathrm{Var}(S)=\lambda E[X^2]=3\cdot\tfrac{1}{2}=\tfrac{3}{2}\). Alternatively: \(E[N]\mathrm{Var}(X)+\mathrm{Var}(N)(E[X])^2=3\cdot\tfrac{1}{4}+3\cdot\tfrac{1}{4}=\tfrac{3}{2}\).</p>]]></text></generalfeedback>
